<section id="Annotate">
<div class="page-header">
<h1>How To Annotate?</h1>
</div>
<p>We have created an interface to aid you in this annotation tasks. On the Annotate page, you will be presented with 2 papers: The citing paper and the cited paper.</p>
<p>For the citing paper, you will only be shown the <b>citing context</b>, i.e. the part of the citing paper that contains the in-text citation.</p>
<p>For the cited paper, you will be shown the entire paper. For the citation, you will determine the type of citation, and select the lines which you think is where the cited information.</p>
<h2>General Steps</h2>
<%= form_tag(nil, :class => "well") do %>
<ol>
	<li>Go to the Annotate page.</li>
	<li>Enter your NUS matric or MTurk ID. You should now see the citing context, and the cited paper.</li>
	<li>Read the citing context on the left side of the page.</li>
	<li>On the right side of the page, decide on the type of the citation, and select one of the options. You are only to select or make changes to your selection (in the cited paper) if you choose Specific.</li>
	<li>If you think the citation is a Specific one, read the cited paper, and click to select the lines which you think is where the cited information.</li>
	<li>Click "Submit Annotations" to submit the annotations for <b>this</b> record. Once submitted, you will be presented another record for you to annotate.</li>
	<li>If you wish to end your session, <b>remember to click on "Quit Annotating" at the top-right of the page</b>. If you annotated some records, you will be presented with a MD5 hash, which facilitates your payment on MTurk. To view past MD5 hash generated for you, "log in" by entering your NUS matric or MTUrk ID, and click on "My Annotations" on the top navigation bar.</li>
</ol>
<% end %>
